<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-495-770  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 495 770.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Iandamp;CS (Instrumentation andamp; Control Systems)  April 1990 v63 n4p87(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Modern digital data converters are fast and affordable.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dehne, Tim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A system programmer who must integrate devices that use differentprotocols will find a digital data converter a simple andaffordable solution.andP;  Integrating two protocols does provide thebenefits of each standard, but it also provides the restrictionsof each and both benefits and restrictions should be reviewedbefore selecting a converter.andP;  One widely used data conversion isbetween Small Computer Systems Interface (SCSI) and GPIB, alsoknown as IEEE-488.andP;  SCSI is usually used to interconnect acomputer and storage devices.andP;  GPIB is usually used tointerconnect a variety of programmable instrumentation or forhigh-speed computer-to-computer communication.andP;  The two standardsare very similar.andP;  Both define a high-speed, parallelcommunication protocol and bus management capabilities.andP;  Only twoSCSI devices are involved at a time in SCSI communications.andP;  Onedevice is an initiator and one is a target.andP;  GPIB has a systemcontroller, a talker, and a listener.andP;  Converters available todaycan be used with a number of host systems in a number of differentapplications with little or no programming effort.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     General Purpose Interface BusSmall Computer Systems InterfaceConvertersSignal ProcessingStandards.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>